name: Roasted goose
instructions: Preheat your oven to 350°F (175°C). Remove the giblets and excess fat from the cavity of the goose. Save the giblets for making stock or gravy. Prick the skin of the goose all over with a fork (without piercing the meat) to help release the fat during cooking. This will result in a crispier skin.
Pat the goose dry with paper towels and then season generously inside and out with salt and pepper. Stuff the cavity with the quartered onion, oranges, crushed garlic, and fresh herbs.
Truss the goose if desired, to help it cook evenly. This involves tying the legs together with kitchen twine and tucking the wings underneath the bird.

Place the goose on a rack in a roasting pan, breast side up. Roast the goose in the preheated oven. Cooking times vary, but as a general guide, calculate about 15-20 minutes per pound (500 grams). Baste the goose occasionally with the drippings.
Use a meat thermometer to ensure the goose reaches an internal temperature of 165°F (74°C) in the thickest part of the thigh without touching the bone.
ingredients: 2-3 sprigs of fresh thyme or rosemary
2 tablespoons melted butter or olive oil

name: Chocolate mousse
instructions: Melt the chopped chocolate in a heatproof bowl set over a pan of simmering water (double boiler) or in short bursts in the microwave, stirring frequently until smooth. Remove from heat and let it cool slightly.
In a clean, dry bowl, whip the egg whites with a pinch of salt until they form stiff peaks. Set aside.

In another bowl, whip the heavy cream until it forms soft peaks. Set aside. In a separate bowl, whisk the egg yolks, sugar, and vanilla extract together until well combined. Gradually pour the slightly cooled melted chocolate into the egg yolk mixture, whisking continuously until well combined.

Gently fold the whipped cream into the chocolate mixture until no streaks remain. Then, fold in the whipped egg whites in batches, being careful not to deflate the mixture. Fold until the mixture is homogeneous.
Spoon or pour the chocolate mousse into serving glasses or a serving bowl. Refrigerate the mousse for at least 2-3 hours, or until set.

name: Braised Red Cabbage
instructions: In a large pot or Dutch oven, melt the butter or heat the olive oil over medium heat. Add the sliced onions and sauté until they begin to soften, about 3-4 minutes.
Stir in the thinly sliced red cabbage and chopped apples. Cook for another 5 minutes, stirring occasionally.

Pour in the red wine vinegar, apple cider or juice, brown sugar or honey, ground cinnamon, ground cloves, salt, and pepper. Stir well to combine. Cover the pot and simmer over low heat for about 45 minutes to 1 hour, stirring occasionally, until the cabbage is tender.

Taste and adjust the seasoning if needed. Add a bit more vinegar or sugar to balance the flavors if desired. Serve the braised red cabbage as a side dish alongside your roast goose. It adds a wonderful sweet and tangy flavor that complements the richness of the goose.
ingredients: 1/4 cup apple cider or apple juice

name: Roasted turkey
instructions: Thaw the turkey completely if it's frozen. Remove giblets and neck from the cavity. Preheat your oven to 325°F (165°C). Pat the turkey dry with paper towels.

Season the cavity generously with salt and pepper. Add aromatics like quartered onion, halved lemon, garlic cloves, and herbs. Gently separate the skin from the breast meat using your fingers. Rub softened butter or olive oil underneath the skin and all over the turkey. Season the skin with salt, pepper, and herbs.

Place the turkey breast side up on a roasting rack in a roasting pan. Cover the breast loosely with foil to prevent it from over-browning. Remove the foil during the last hour of cooking. Roast the turkey in the preheated oven. The cooking time will depend on the size of the turkey. As a general guide, calculate about 15 minutes per pound (500 grams). Baste the turkey every 30-45 minutes with the juices or melted butter.

The turkey is done when a meat thermometer inserted into the thickest part of the thigh (without touching the bone) reads 165°F (75°C). Also, the juices should run clear when you pierce the turkey between the leg and body.

Once done, remove the turkey from the oven, tent it loosely with foil, and let it rest for at least 20-30 minutes. This allows the juices to redistribute and the turkey to be more flavorful and easier to carve.

name: Christmas pudding
instructions: In a large mixing bowl, combine the dried fruit, dates, figs, and candied peel. Add the apple juice or orange juice, dark brown sugar, orange zest, lemon zest, melted butter, and beaten eggs. Mix well.
Sift in the flour, ground cinnamon, nutmeg, cloves, and baking soda. Stir until well combined. The mixture should be moist but not too runny.
Grease a heatproof bowl or pudding basin with butter. Spoon the pudding mixture into the greased bowl.

Cover the bowl with a double layer of pleated greaseproof paper or foil, securing it tightly with string. Place the bowl in a large pot and fill the pot with water about halfway up the side of the bowl. Cover the pot and steam the pudding for about 2-3 hours. Check occasionally and top up the water if needed.

name: Roasted Potatos
instructions: Preheat your oven to 425°F (220°C). Peel the potatoes and cut them into chunks or quarters, ensuring they are roughly the same size for even cooking.

Place the potatoes in a large pot, cover with cold salted water, and bring to a boil. Let them boil for about 5-7 minutes until the edges start to soften but the centers are still firm. This helps create a crispy exterior.
Drain the parboiled potatoes and return them to the pot. Shake the pot vigorously to roughen up the edges of the potatoes. This helps create a crispy texture.

Place a roasting pan in the preheated oven with the olive oil or melted fat, allowing it to heat for a few minutes. Carefully add the potatoes to the hot oil or fat in the roasting pan. Toss them gently to coat with the oil. Season the potatoes generously with salt and pepper. Add herbs and garlic cloves, if using, for extra flavor.

Place the roasting pan back into the oven. Roast the potatoes for about 45 minutes to 1 hour, turning them occasionally with a spatula or spoon to ensure they cook evenly. The potatoes should be golden brown and crispy on the outside and tender on the inside when done.
ingredients: 1/4 cup olive oil or melted duck fat/goose fat for extra richness
